              {
                "id": "prepare-rural-questions",
                "name": "Prepare Questions for Our Rural Heating Specialist",
                "description": "Write down questions to maximize value from your service call:\n\n**Good Questions for Rural Properties:**\n- What caused this problem?\n- Is this common with propane furnaces?\n- How can I prevent this in the future?\n- Should I consider heat pump to reduce propane costs?\n- Is my furnace properly sized for my square footage?\n- Should I consider backup heating options?\n- What maintenance should I do myself?\n- How does my propane consumption compare to similar homes?\n- Are there any safety concerns?\n- What's the expected lifespan of this repair?\n\n**Questions About Rural-Specific Costs:**\n- What's included in rural service pricing?\n- Any travel charges to Rillito?\n- Warranty on parts and labor?\n- Financing options available?\n- Should I file insurance claim? (if applicable)\n\n**Why This Matters:** Our technicians average 16+ years experience including extensive rural property expertise. Ask questions—we're here to educate and optimize your rural heating system.",
                "duration": "10 minutes",
                "tools": ["Notepad with prepared rural-specific questions"]
              },
              {
                "id": "after-heating-repair-expectations",
                "name": "What to Expect After Heating Repair in Rillito",
                "description": "Understanding what happens after our technician completes your heating repair ensures you get maximum value:\n\n**Immediate Post-Repair:**\n- **System Testing:** Technician will run furnace through multiple heating cycles (15-30 minutes) to verify proper operation, check temperature rise across heat exchanger, and ensure all safety controls function correctly\n- **Combustion Analysis:** For gas/propane furnaces, we test combustion efficiency, CO levels, and O2 levels to ensure safe, efficient operation\n- **Walkthrough & Education:** Explanation of what was repaired, why it failed, and how to prevent future issues\n- **Written Documentation:** Detailed invoice showing work performed, parts installed, warranty information, and maintenance recommendations\n- **ServiceTitan Email:** Within 2 hours, automated email with full service report, before/after photos, and feedback link\n\n**First Week After Repair:**\n- **Monitor Performance:** Furnace should maintain temperature easily, run normal heating cycles (15-20 minutes on, then off until temperature drops), distribute heat evenly to all rooms, and operate without unusual sounds\n- **Warning Signs:** Contact us immediately if you notice: no heat or inadequate heating, short-cycling (on/off every few minutes), unusual sounds not present before, gas smell (CALL 911 first, then us), or excessive propane consumption\n- **Follow-Up:** Our quality assurance team may call 3-5 days after service to verify satisfaction\n\n**Warranty & Long-Term:**\n- **Parts Warranty:** Manufacturer parts warranties (typically 1-10 years depending on component)\n- **Labor Warranty:** Our workmanship guaranteed 1 year from service date\n- **Maintenance Reminder:** Schedule annual tune-up 6 months after repair to maintain optimal performance\n- **Rural Property Monitoring:** Keep eye on propane consumption and heating performance through winter season\n\n**Emergency Contact:** Save our 24/7 number: **(520) 333-2665**—available anytime for Rillito heating emergencies.",
                "duration": "Ongoing monitoring",
                "tools": ["Save emergency contact number", "Monitor system performance"]
              },
              {
                "id": "check-propane-tank-delivery-schedule",
                "name": "Verify Propane Tank Level and Delivery Schedule",
                "description": "For rural Rillito properties relying on propane heating, tank management is critical:\n\n**Why This Matters:**\n- Running out of propane during heating season causes emergency\n- Propane delivery can take 2-5 days in rural areas\n- Low tank levels can affect gas pressure and furnace performance\n- Winter propane prices often higher than summer\n\n**Before Service Call:**\n- Check current propane tank gauge level (aim to keep above 30%)\n- Note your propane supplier name and account number\n- Review recent propane delivery receipts for consumption patterns\n- Calculate approximate days remaining at current usage rate\n- Schedule propane delivery if below 40% during heating season\n\n**Propane Consumption Patterns:**\n- 2,500 sq ft home: 200-300 gallons per winter season\n- 3,500 sq ft home: 350-500 gallons per winter season\n- 5,000 sq ft home: 500-750 gallons per winter season\n\n**Questions to Ask Technician:**\n- Is my propane consumption normal for my home size?\n- Could furnace inefficiency be increasing propane use?\n- Would heat pump reduce my propane costs significantly?\n- Are there signs of gas pressure issues affecting performance?\n\n**Rural Rillito Considerations:** Many Rillito properties are on propane delivery routes that run weekly or bi-weekly. Don't wait until tank is critically low. Winter weather can delay deliveries, and running completely empty requires purging and pressure testing before refilling.",
                "duration": "15 minutes",
                "tools": ["Propane tank gauge reading", "Delivery receipts", "Supplier contact info"]
              },
              {
                "id": "document-energy-efficiency-concerns",
                "name": "Document Energy Bills and Efficiency Concerns",
                "description": "Track your heating costs to identify potential efficiency problems:\n\n**Why This Matters for Rural Properties:**\n- Large homes and long duct runs increase energy waste potential\n- Propane costs significant portion of winter budget\n- Efficiency decline often gradual and unnoticed\n- Data helps technician diagnose hidden problems\n\n**Information to Gather:**\n- Last 3-4 months of propane delivery receipts\n- Winter heating costs compared to previous years\n- Square footage and current thermostat settings\n- Age of current heating system\n- Any recent changes to home (additions, insulation, windows)\n\n**Warning Signs of Efficiency Problems:**\n- 20%+ increase in propane consumption vs. last winter (same temperatures)\n- Some rooms always colder than others\n- Furnace runs constantly during cold nights\n- Noticeable temperature swings (4-5°F) throughout day\n- Higher bills despite similar or less usage\n\n**Cost Comparison Data (Bring to Service Call):**\n- Current system: Operating cost per month\n- Years in service and maintenance history\n- Any efficiency testing done previously\n\n**Technician Can Help:**\n- Combustion efficiency testing (should be 80-96% depending on furnace type)\n- Duct leakage testing (often 20-35% on rural homes with long runs)\n- Heat pump feasibility analysis and propane savings calculation\n- Cost-benefit analysis comparing repair vs. high-efficiency replacement\n\n**Rural Rillito Reality:** With propane at $2.80-3.20/gallon and larger homes averaging 3,000-4,500 sq ft, winter heating costs of $350-500/month are common. Heat pump conversions can reduce this to $180-250/month—$170-250 monthly savings that pays for system in 5-7 years. Bring your bills so we can show you exact savings potential for YOUR property.",
